n struggling to positively manoeuvre themselves and negotiate their identities into positions of contestation and control over marginalizing discourses which disempower them as ‘others’ within Japanese society as they begin to mature. Paradoxically, at other times, within more empowering alternative discourses of ethnicity, they also enjoy and celebrate cultural, symbolic, social and linguistic capital which they discursively create for themselves as they come to terms with their constructed identities of “Japaneseness”, “whiteness” and “halfness/doubleness”. This book has a colourful storyline throughout - narrated in the girls’ own voices - that follows them out of childhood and into the rapid physical and emotional growth years of early adolescence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aIdentity (Psychology)xCase studiesxSocial aspectsxJapan. 0aIdentity (Psychology)xSocial aspectszJapanvCase studies. 0aLanguage and culturexCase studiesxJapan. 0aLanguage and culturezJapanvCase studies. 0aRacially mixed childrenxEthnic identityxJapan. 0aRacially mixed childrenzJapanxEthnic identity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / General.2bisacsh  aConstructed identities .  aDiscourse analysis.  aEthnicity.  aGender.  aHalf-Japanese girls.  aHybrid identities .  aHybrid identity construction.  aIdentity construction.  aJapaneseness.  aMixed-race identities.  aMultiethnicity.  aWhiteness.1 aNorton, Bonny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPennycook, Alastair, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertMultiLingual Matters Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066313608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertMultiLingual Matters eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311060671